More recently, Gao et al. [136] conducted an interesting study on an Li1.13Mn0.54Ni0.13Co0.14O2 cathode material using ALD. In the work, the researchers performed an ALD process of iron oxide (FeOx) on the cathode powders and annealed the coated powders. The powders were coated in a fluidized‐bed ALD with different ALD cycles at 450 °C, i.e., 0, 20, 40, and 100 cycles, and named as UC, 20Fe, 40Fe, and 100Fe, respectively. Furthermore, these coated and uncoated powders were annealed at 700 °C in air for 24 h and cooled naturally, and named as AUC, A20Fe, A40Fe, and A100Fe, respectively. Using XPS and TEM, Gao et al. [136] analyzed the annealing effects. They found that the annealing led to the diffusion of Fe into the structure of the Li1.13Mn0.54Ni0.13Co0.14O2 material. TEM analyzed the annealed sample locally [Fig. 7(a)]. The fast Fourier transform (FFT) pattern [Figs. (7b)–(7d)] generated from Fig. 7(a) suggested that the surface spinel coating was formed and completely epitaxially grown on the inner lattice of the Li1.13Mn0.54Ni0.13Co0.14O2 material with the epitaxial growth relationships as follows: [110]R//[110]spinel, (300)R//(1¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
